name: Cornelius Lentulus, Lucius.
bio: Sardinia,Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 211 BC.

name: Manlius Vulso, P.
bio: Sardinia,Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 210 BC.

name: Aurunculeius, C.
bio: Sardinia,Republican moneyer and Praetor of Sardinia in

name: (Terentius) Varro, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a younger relative of the C. Terentius Varro who was Consul in 216 BC.

name: Aelius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cornelius Dolabella, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the Cn. Cornelius Dolabella who was Rex Sacrorum 208-180 BC.

name: Aelius
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: L[utatius] C[erco] / C[atulus], Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: (Terentius) Var[ro]
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the A. Terentius Varro who was Praetor in 184 BC.

name: (Caecilius) Metellus
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably an otherwise unattested cousin of the Q. Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus who was Consul in 143 BC.

name: (Baebius) Tampilus
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably either the Cn. Baebius Tampilus who was Praetor in 168, or his cousin, M. Baebius Tampilus, who was Consul in 181 BC.

name: Pl[autius] H[ypsaeus], L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the son of the L. Plautius Hypsaeus who was Praetor in 189 BC.

name: Maenius, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the grandfather of the P. Maenius Ant[ias] M.f (q.v.) who issued coins in 132 BC. He may also related to the Q. Maenius who was Praetor in 186, or a variety of other praetors from the Maenii.

name: Todus
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.
appear: symbol of a bird and TOD

name: Maenius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the Q. Maenius who was Praetor in 170 BC

name: Furius Philus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Furius Philus who was Praetor in 171 BC.

name: Autronius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Autronius whom the elder Cato defended.

name: Domitius Ahenobarbus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus who was Consul in 162 BC.

name: Marius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Mamilius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Titinius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a son of the M. Titinius who was Praetor Urb. in 178 BC, or of the M. Titinius Curvus who was Praetor in Nearer Spain in 178 BC.

name: Furius, S.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Q[uinctilius], Sextus
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a son of the P. Quinctilius Varus who was Praetor in 203 BC.

name: Calpurnius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the father of the Cn. Calpusnius Piso who was Consul in 139. He may also be the son of the Cn. Calpurnius who was an officer during the Second Punic War.

name: Coelius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Coelius who was Legate 170-169 BC.

name: (Furius) Purpurio
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a son of the L. Furius Purpurio who was Consul in 196 BC.

name: (Iuventius) Thalna
bio: Republican moneyer, may be identified with the P. Iuventius Thalna who was praetor in 149 BC.

name: Matienus
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cluvius Saxula, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a son of the C. Cluvius Saxula who was Praetor in 173 BC and older brother to the moneyer (Cluvius) Saxula.

name: Caecilius, A.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a son of the A. Caecilius who was Aedile of the Plebs in 189 BC.

name: Sae[nius], C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Pae[tus]
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. The name is an uncertain resolution of the monogram on the coins.

name: (Cornelius) Cinna, (L.)
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the L. Cornelius Cinna who was Consul in 127 BC. He came to the Consulship much later than his career as a moneyer, as befits the first of his family line to attain the Consulship.

name: Balbus
bio: Republican moneyer, who cannot be identified from the uncertain cognomen Balbus; he may be an Acilius or a Naevius.

name: (Cluvius) Saxula
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the younger brother of the moneyer  C. Cluvius Saxula and son of the C. Cluvius Saxula who was praetor in 173 BC.

name: (Terentius) Var[r]o
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the A. Terentius Varro who was commissioner to L. Mummius (Consul, 146 BC).

name: (Licinius) Murena, (L.)
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Licinius Murena who was the great-grandfather of the L. Licinius Murena who was Consul in 62 BC. The great-grandfather held the praetorship presumably before his appointment as commissioner to L. Mummius who was Consul in 146.

name: (Furius) Purpurio
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Opeimi[us]
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the Q. Opimius who was Consul in 154 BC.

name: Cornelius Blasio, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the P. Cornelius P.f. Blasio who was Praetor in the 140s BC (praetorship attested in SEG iii, 451).

name: Opei[mius]
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the Q. Opimius who was Consul in 154 BC.

name: Val[erius]
bio: Republican moneyer (presumably a Valerius), known only from his coins marked with the monogram VAL.

name: (Papirius) Turdus
bio: Republican moneyer, may be a son of the C. Papirius Turdus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 177 BC.

name: (Atilius) Saranus
bio: Republican moneyer, may be the Sextus Atilius Serranus/Saranus who was Consul in 136

name: (Pinarius) Nat(ta)
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Scribonius, C.
bio: This may be the C. Scribonius who was Praef. Soc. in 181 BC, the son of C. Scribonius who was Praetor in 193 BC.

name: (Iuventius) Thalna, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Maianius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Saufeius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cornelius Sulla, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the uncle of Lucius Cornelius Sulla, the one-time dictator of Rome. Alternatively, he may be the dictator's grandfather, depending on how one reads the generations in Velleius ii, 17,2.

name: Safra
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: (Decimius) Flavus
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He may be a grandson of the C. Decimus Flavus who was Praetor in 184 BC.

name: (Pinarius) Natta
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: It[e]i[us], L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Iunius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Consul in 143 BC.

name: Atilius Saranus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, may be a son of the M. Atilius Serranus who was Praetor in 152 BC.

name: Marcius Libo, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Sempronius Pitio, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Terentius Lucanus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the Terentius Lucanus who is master of Terence (Suetonius, Vita Terenti I), or this man's son.

name: Cupiennius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Antestius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. Many of his coins feature a dog; if this is considered significant, it may indicate that the moneyer's cognomen is Catulus.

name: Iunius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, a member of the Iunii Silanii, but the family tree is difficult to reconstruct.

name: Annius Rufus, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the T. Annius Rufus who was Consul in 128 BC.

name: Curiatius Trigeminus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the father of the C. Curiatius who issued coins in 135 BC. He is probably also the C. Curiatius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 138 BC.

name: Iulius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He is probably not from the branch of Iulii Caesares but a different branch of the Julian family.

name: Atilius Nomentanus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Atilius Nomentanus who was on the staff of Q. Mucius Scaevola during Scaevola's praetorship in Asia in 120 BC. His coins have NOM in place of the usual legend ROMA.

name: Titinius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Aufidius Rusticus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly a brother of T. Ofidius / Aufidius M.f. Pop (one of the senators associated with the decree de Ambraciotibus et Athamanibus)

name: Valerius Flaccus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the grandson of the C. Valerius Flaccus who was Praetor in 183 BC, and the father of the C. Valerius Flaccus who was Consul in 93 BC.

name: Aurelius Cotta, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the father of C. Aurelius, M. Aurelius, and L. Aurelius Cotta (Consuls in 75, 74, and 65 BC respectively). He may also be the younger son of the L. Aurelius Cotta who was Consul in 144 BC.

name: Spuri[us], A.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. The interpretation of his name is uncertain.

name: Renius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Gellius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the historian Cn. Gellius.

name: (Aelius) Paetus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, primarily known from his coins; he may be a grandson of the Q. Aelius P.f. Q.n. Paetus who was Consul in 167.

name: Veturius, Tiberius
bio: Republican moneyer, likely the son of T. Veturius Gracchi who was Augur from 174 BC.

name: Pompeius, Sextus
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the Sextus Pompeius who was Praetor around 119 BC and the father of Cn. Pompeius Strabo.

name: Baebius Tampilus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. However, he may be the father of the M. Baebius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 103 BC. He is presumably descended from one of the Consular Baebii Tampili of the early second century.

name: Lucretius Trio, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Antestius Gragulus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. The jackdaw ('graculus') on some of his coins is an allusion to the moneyer's cognomen. He may be the L. Antestius mentioned in a Senate decree de agro Pergamo.

name: Servilius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He is not the C. Servilius in Cicero's list of provincial governors (div. in Caec. 63).

name: Curiatius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the son of the C. Curiatius Trigeminus who issued coins in 142 BC. His coins are marked C·CVR·F TRIGE (C. Curiatius filius Trigeminus).

name: Trebanius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Minucius Augurinus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the brother of the Tiberius Minucius C.f. Augurinus (Tiberius Minucius q.v.) who issued coins in 134 BC.

name: Minucius, Tiberius
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the brother of the C. Minucius Augurinus (q.v.) who issued coins in 135 BC.

name: Aburius Geminus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, primarily known from his coins; he may be descended from the C. Aburius who was Legate in 171 BC.

name: Marcius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Numitorius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the C. Numitorius C.f. Lem. who was mentioned in the Senatus Consultum de agro Pergameno.

name: Calpurnius, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the father of the P. Calpurnius Lanarius who was legate in 81 BC (the only other Republican Calpurnius with the praenomen Publius).

name: Minucius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, may be the father of L. Minucius Basilus.

name: Maenius Ant[ias], P.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably descended from the P. Maenius (q.v.) who issued coins in the 190s BC. He presumably claimed descent from C. Maenius, the Consul in 338 BC who conquered Antium.

name: Aburius Geminus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, primarily known from his coins; he may be descended from the M. Aburius who was Praetor in 176 BC.

name: Fabrinius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Postumius Albinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins, but probably the son of L. Postumius Albinus (Consul 154 BC).

name: Opimius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Opimius who was Consul in 121 BC.

name: Opimius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins, but is presumably the brother of the L. Opimius (q.v.) who issued coins in the same year (131 BC).

name: Acilius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Caecilius Metellus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Q. Caecilius Metellus who was Consul in 123 BC.

name: Vargunteius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Iulius Caesar, Sextus
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Sextus Iulius Caesar who was Praetor in 123 BC.

name: (Marcius) Philippus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the grandson of the Q. Marcius Philippus who was Consul in 186 and 169 BC.

name: Cloelius, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, the father of the T. Cloelius (or Cloulius) (q.v.) who was Legate in 83 BC. He may be the T. Cloelius of Cicero's Rosc. Am. 64.

name: Domitius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, a relative of the Cn. Domitius (q.v.) who issued coins in 116 to 115 BC, though from a different branch of the family.

name: Caecilius Metellus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, either the L. Caecilius Metellus Delmaticus who was Consul in 119 BC or the L. Caecilius Metellus Diadematus who was Consul in 117 BC and whose three brothers all held the moneyership.His coins are marked with an elephant's head, possibly a reference to the capture of Hasdrubal's elephants in 250 BC by L. Caecilius Metellus.

name: Cassius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the son of the C. Cassius Longinus (q.v.) who was Consul in 124 BC.

name: Quinctius Flamininus, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the son of the T. Quinctius Flamininus who was Consul in 123 BC.

name: Fabius Pictor, N.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the grandson of the Q. Fabius Pictor who was Praetor in 189 and Flamen Quirinalis; he is also presumably the son of the Numerius Fabius Pictor whose name should be restored in Cicero, Brutus 81.

name: Caecilius Metellus Caprarius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the C. Caecilius Metellus Caprarius who was Consul in 113 BC.

name: Porcius Laeca, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Acilius Balbus, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Mn. Acilius Balbus who was Consul in 114 BC.

name: Fabius Labeo, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the grandson of the Q. Fabius Labeo who was Consul in 183 BC and the son of the Q. Fabius Labeo mentioned in Cicero, Brutus 81.

name: Porcius Cato, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the C. Porcius Cato who was Consul in 114 BC.

name: Fannius C.f., M.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the son of the C. Fannius who was Consul in 122.

name: Papirius Carbo, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who may be identified with the Praetor of Sicily mentioned by Cicero in fam. Ix, 21,3.

name: Minucius Rufus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Q. Minucius Rufus who was Legate in 110 BC and elder brother of the Consul of 110 BC.

name: Plautius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the son of the C. Plautius who was Praetor in 146.

name: Papirius Carbo, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Cn. Papirius Carbo who was Consul in 113 BC.

name: Tullius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He may be the father of M. Tullius Decula (Consul, 81 BC).

name: Furius Philus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the son of L. Furius Philus, who was Consul in 136 BC.

name: Aurelius Scaurus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the late second-century Quaestor in Cicero's div. in Caec. and in Verr. (63 and 85 BC). He was the son of the M. Aurelius Scaurus who was Consul in 108 BC and father of M. Aurelius M.f. Vol. He issued coins in Narbo jointly with the other monetary magistrates, L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.), L. Pomponius (q.v.) and L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.).

name: Cosconius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the son of the M. Cosconius who was Praetor in 135 BC. He issued coins in Narbo jointly with the other monetary magistrates, L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.), L. Pomponius (q.v.) and L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.).

name: Licinius Crassus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer and Consul in 95 BC. He issued coins in Narbo in 118 BC as a senior monetary magistrate, jointly with the other monetary magistrates Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.), L. Pomponius (q.v.) and L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.).

name: Pomponius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the father of the Cn. Pomponius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 90 BC. He issued coins in Narbo jointly with the other monetary magistrates L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.) and L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.).

name: Porcius Licinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the grandson or great-grandson of L. Porcius Licinus who was Consul in 184 BC. He issued coins in Narbo jointly with the other monetary magistrates L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.) and L. Pomponius (q.v.).

name: Malleolus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the father of the C. Publicius Malleolus who was Quaestor in 80 BC and issued coins in the late 90s BC. He issued coins in Narbo jointly with the other monetary magistrates L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.) and L. Pomponius (q.v.).

name: Marcius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He issued coins (marked Q·MAR) jointly with two other moneyers known only by their initials C F and L R.

name: Caecilius Metellus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, identified with the mint in Rome in 117 to 116 BC and probably the Q. Caecilius Metellus Nepos who was Consul in 98 BC. Alternatively, the moneyer may be Q. Caecilius Metellus Numidicus, Consul in 109 BC. His coins are marked Q·MET and issued jointly with M. Calidius (q.v.) and Cn. Fulvius (q.v.).

name: Calidius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, may be the father of the Q. Calidius who was Praetor in 79 BC. He issued coins jointly with Q. Caecilius Metellus (q.v.) and Cn. Fulvius (q.v.).

name: Fulvius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. These were issued jointly with Q. Caecilius Metellus (q.v.) and M. Calidius (q.v.).

name: Curtius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. These were issued jointly with Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.) and M. Silanus (q.v.).

name: Silanus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, difficult to identify, though his family is known. He issued coins jointly with Cn. Domitius Ahenobarbus (q.v.) and Q. Curtius (q.v.).

name: Sergius Silus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, not known to have progressed beyond the quaestorship. He is not the father of Cataline (Lucius Sergius Silus, q.v.), but belongs to another branch of the family.

name: Cetegus
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the father of the notorius political boss of the 70s BC, P. Cethegus.

name: Cipius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. Some speculate that he may be identified with a certain M. Cipius in Cicero's fam. Vii, 24, 1.

name: Fonteius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, a brother or cousin of the moneyer Mn. Fonteius (q.v.); either may be identified with the Fonteius who was Legate in 91.

name: Aemilius Lepidus, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the Mn. Aemilius Lepidus attested by the filiation of Mn. Aemilius Mn.f. Lepidus (Consul, 66 BC).  He may be the son of M. Aemilius Lepidus (Consul, 126 BC)

name: Licinius Nerva, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the P. Licinius Nerva who was Praetor in 104 BC.

name: Marcius Philippus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Marcius Philippus who was Consul in  91 BC.

name: Didius, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the T. Didius who was Consul in 98 BC.

name: Manlius Torquatus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, not known to have progressed beyond the quaestorship, which office he held while issuing coins.

name: Cornelius Blasio, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, a descendant of the Cn. Cornelius Blasio who was Praetor in 194 BC.

name: Q[uinctius?], Ti.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Caesius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Claudius Pulcher, Appius
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Appius Claudius Pulcher who was Praetor in 89 BC and Consul in 79 BC.  He issued coins jointly with T. Manlius Mancinus (q.v.) and Q. Urbinus (q.v.).

name: Manlius Mancinus, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, may be the T. Manlius Mancinus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 107 BC.  He issued coins jointly with Appius Claudius Pulcher (q.v.) and Q. Urbinus (q.v.).

name: Urbinus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.  He issued coins jointly with Appius Claudius Pulcher (q.v.) and T. Manlius Mancinus (q.v.).

name: Claudius Pulcher, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the C. Claudius Pulcher who was Consul in 92 BC.

name: Porcius Laeca, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the P. Porcius Laeca who was Tribune of the Plebs in the 90s BC.

name: Flaminius Chilo, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Aquillius, Mn
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Mn. Aquillius who was Consul in 101 BC. If the identification is correct, he was a supporter of Gaius Marius (who ran for Consul with him in 101 BC). He was given a triumph in 100 BC for his handling of an insurgency in Sicily; he was subsequently accused of maladministration in Sicily but was acquitted because of his former bravery. He died when captured during the Mithridatic war; Mithridates tortured him and poured molten gold down Aquillius' throat.

name: Memmius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer and the brother of the C. Memmius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 111 BC. He may be identified with the L. Memmius who visited Egypt as a senator in 112 BC.

name: Lutatius Cerco, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, not known to have progressed beyond the quaestorship, which office he held while issuing coins.

name: Valerius Flaccus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the L. Valerius Flaccus who was Consul in 100 BC.

name: Fonteius, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, a brother of cousin of the moneyer C. Fonteius (q.v.).

name: Herennius, M
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the M. Herennius who was Consul in 93 BC.

name: Manlius, A.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the A. Manlius who was Legate from 107-105 BC. It is not known if the SER relates to the cognomen Sergianus.

name: Cornelius Sisenna, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He is to be distinguished from the Cn. Cornelius Sisenna who was Praetor around 119 BC.

name: Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus who was Consul in 83 BC.

name: Sulpicius, C
bio: Republican moneyer, a son of the C. Sulpicius Galba who was IIIVIR ADA around 120 BC and was exiled in 109. The moneyer is also a brother of the Ser. Sulpicius C.f. Galba who was on the consilium of Pompeius Strabo at Asculum.

name: Aurelius Cotta, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Aurelius Cotta who was Tribune of the Plebs in 103 BC and Praetor in (possibly) 95 BC.

name: Hostilius Tubulus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, likely to have been a descendant of the L. Hostilius Tubulus who was Praetor in 142 BC.

name: Thorius Balbus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, Legate in 79 BC

name: Appuleius Saturninus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Appuleius Saturninus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 103 and 100 BC

name: Coelius Caldus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the C. Coelius Caldus who was Consul in 94 BC and the father of the C. Coelius Caldus (q.v.) who issued coins in 51 BC.

name: Minucius Thermus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Q. Minucius M.f. Ter. on the consilium of Pompeius Strabo at Asculum, perhaps as legate.

name: Iulius Caesar, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Julius Caesar who was Consul in 90 BC.

name: Cassius Caecianus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Fabius, C
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly C. Fabius Hadrianus who was Praetor in 84 BC.

name: Iulius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He is probably not from the branch of Iulii Caesares but a different branch of the Julian family. Not to be confused with the moneyer of RRC 224 with the same name and signature.

name: Lucilius Rufus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the son of Mn. Lucilius M.f. and perhaps the father of M. Lucilius (Tribune of the Plebs ca. 64 BC).

name: Sentius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, the brother of C. Sentius C.f. who was Praetor in 94 BC. The moneyer was himself a praetor between 93 and 89 BC.

name: Fundanius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while Quaestor in 101 BC; he is not known to have progressed past this office.  He may be the father of the C. Fundanius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 68 BC.

name: Servilius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the brother of P. Servilius C.f. M.n. Vatia Isauricus, who was Consul in 79 BC.

name: Servilius Rullus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, the father of the P. Servilius Rullus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 63 BC.

name: Cornelius Lentulus Marcellinus, P.
bio: The moneyer is a son of M. Claudius Marcellus, and father of the moneyer Cn. Lentulus who was Consul in 56 BC.

name: Calpurnius Piso (Caesoninus), L.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the L. Calpurnius Piso Caesoninus who was Praetor in 90 BC and was an owner of an arms factory during the Social War. He also would have been author of a Lex Calpurnia offering citizenship to certain categories of allies during the war. He was the father of the L. Calpurnius Piso Caesoninus who was Consul in 58 BC. He issued coins jointly with Q. Servilius Caepio (q.v.).

name: Servilius Caepio, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the Q. Servilius Caepio who was Praetor in circa 91 BC. He issued coins as Quaestor Urbanus jointly with L. Calpurnius Piso (Caesoninus) (q.v.)

name: Sabinus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer (possibly P. Vettius Sabinus) who issued coins while Quaestor, beyond which office he is not known to have progressed.

name: Cloelius, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the son of T. Cloelius (q.v.) who issued coins in 128 BC. He was a partisan of Marius' and was legate in 83 BC.

name: Egnatuleius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who produced coins while Quaestor in 97 BC. He is not known to have progressed past the quaestorship.

name: Pomponius Molo, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Caecilius Metellus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the L. Metellus who was Praetor in 71 BC. He issued coins jointly with A. Postumius Albinus (q.v.) and C. Publicius Malleolus (q.v.)

name: Postumius Albinus, A.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly killed in the Battle of the Colline Gate in 82 BC. He was probably the son of Sp. Postumius Albinus, Consul in 110 BC. He issued coins jointly with L. Caecilius Metellus (q.v.) and C. Publicius Malleolus (q.v.).

name: Publicius Malleolus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Quaestor in 80 BC. He issued coins jointly with L. Caecilius Metellus (q.v.) and A. Postumius Albinus (q.v.).

name: Allius Bala, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Iunius Silanus, D.
bio: Republican moneyer, descended from the D. Iunius Silanus who was Praetor in 141 and born a Manlius Torquatus.

name: Calpurnius Piso Frugi, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 74 BC.

name: Titius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Vibius Pansa, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably the adoptive father of the C. Vibius Pansa Caetronianus who issued coins in 48 BC. He was also proscribed by Sulla (Dio xlv, 17, 1).

name: Porcius Cato, M.
bio: Republican moneyer whose identity is uncertain (he may possibly have been a wine-merchant). He is likely not to have been related to the brance of the Cato Uticenses.

name: Titurius Sabinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Legate in 75 BC.

name: Cornelius Lentulus Clodianus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Consul in 72 BC.

name: Marcius Censorinus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who was a partisan of Marius and died as legate in 82 BC during the final struggle against Sulla.

name: Fonteius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, was praetor in 75 BC and was a client of Cicero. He seems to have been a moneyer sometime before his quaestorship in 84. None of his coins survive.

name: Rubrius Dossenus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Memmius Gal., C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. These are issued jointly with his brother L. Memmius Gal. (q.v.).  He may be the son of L. Memmius Gal. (q.v.) who issued coins in 106 BC.

name: Memmius Gal., L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. These are issued jointly with his brother C. Memmius Gal. (q.v.). He may be the son of L. Memmius Gal. (q.v.) who issued coins in 106 BC.

name: Critonius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins jointly with M. Fannius (q.v.) while serving as Aedile of the Plebs. He is otherwise unknown.

name: Fannius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins jointly with L. Critonius (q.v.) in 86 BC while serving as Aedile of the Plebs. He later became Praetor in 80 BC.

name: Iulius Bursio, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Fonteius, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the brother of the moneyer M. Fonteius (RRC 347) and a military tribune.

name: Licinius Macer, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, the historian C. Licinius Macer who was Praetor ca. 68 BC.

name: Cassius L.f. Longinus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins in 84 BC jointly with L. Livius Salinator (q.v.). He was Consul in 73 BC and passed the lex Terentia Cassia to buy Sicilian grain and sell it for low prices in Rome. He later fought against the slave Spartacus in Gaul but was unable to stop his revolting mass of followers. He may be the father of the famous C. Cassius Longinus (q.v.), one of the conspirators against Julius Caesar.

name: Livius Salinator, L.
bio: Republican moneyer and Legate of Sertorius in 81 BC. He issued coins with C. Cassius Longinus in 84 BC.

name: Furius Crassipes, P.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while a Curule Aedile in 84 BC. He is not otherwise known.

name: (Iuventius) Laterensis
bio: Republican moneyer, may be identified with the father of the M. Iuventius Laterensis who was Praetor in 51 BC. Alternately, he may be the Praetor Mn. Iuventius L.f. Laterensis.

name: Antonius Balbus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while Praetor in 83-82 BC.

name: Valerius Flaccus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins while Proconsul in Gaul. His issue of coins is associated with Sulla's first moves against Q. Sertorius in Spain.

name: Annius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins in northern Italy and Spain. He was sent against Q. Sertorius in Spain sometime after mid-82 BC. C. Annius may have been in charge of both Spanish provinces and had two quaestors under him (L. Fabius Hispaniensis (q.v.) and C. Tarquitius (q.v.)).

name: Fabius Hispaniensis, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was one of two quaestors under C. Annius (q.v.) and issued coins in Spain. He was later proscribed for switching allegience to Sertorius.

name: Tarquitius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who was one of two quaestors under C. Annius (q.v.).

name: Manlius Torquatus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer and Proquaestor under Sulla, in which capacity he issued coins. He later became Consul in 65 BC.

name: Postumius Albinus, A.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably a grandson of the Sp. Postumius Albinus who was Consul in 110 BC.

name: Caecilius Metellus Pius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who served under Sulla as a commander in the fight against Carrinas, Norbanus, and Carbo. Sulla made him Pontifex Maximus and in 80, Metellus Pius was elected Consul. He won a triumph for his efforts in Hispania, and died around 63 BC.

name: Volumnius Strabo, L.
bio: The moneyer may be the L. Volumnius L.f. Ani. on the consilium of Cn. Pompeius Strabo at Asculum. He could also be the father of the Strabo in Cicero's ad Att. Xii, 17.

name: Marius Capito, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He is notably not related to C. Marius.

name: Procilius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably to be identified with the Senator attested in 56 BC (see Cicero, ad Q.fr. ii, 7). He may also be the man later condemned for misconduct in that year, or he may be the historian Procilius.

name: Publicius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Manlius, A.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while Quaestor in 80 BC. He may be the eldest son of the A. Manlius who issued coins in 117/6 BC.

name: Naevius Balbus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Claudius Nero, Tiberius
bio: Republican moneyer who was a Praetor before 63 BC.

name: Papius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Volteius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cassius Longinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Praetor in 66 BC.

name: Rutilius Flaccus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the senator of 72 BC who appears in Cicero Cluent. 182.

name: Satrienus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Rustius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Lucretius Trio, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Egnatius Maximus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who may appear in Cicero, ad Attl xiii, 34 & 35. He is otherwise known from his coins.

name: Farsuleius Mensor, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Postumius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, may appear in Cicero pro Murena as a prosecutor of Murena and candidate for the praetorship of 62 BC.

name: Cossutius Sabula, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the father of the C. Cossetius Maridianus who issued coins in 44 BC. He is presumably connected with the Roman negotiatores of the same name functioning in the Greek east, and this Greek influence appears on his coinage.

name: Plaetorius (Cestianus), L.
bio: Republican moneyer, not known to have progressed beyond the quaestorship, which office he held while issuing coins. He is presumably the L. Plaetorius who is a senator in 66 BC, according to Cicero Cluent.165

name: Cornelius Lentulus Spinther, P.
bio: Republican moneyer who was consul in 57 BC.

name: Pomponius Rufus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Crepereius Rocus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably a younger brother of the M. Crepereius who was the Military Tribune in 69 BC. He is presumably connected with the Roman negotiatores of the same name functioning in the Greek East. This Greek influence appears on his coinage.

name: Axius Naso, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, attested as a banker on a contemporary tessera nummularia (small bone piece attached to groups of coins for accounting purposes).

name: Aquillius, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer who may be identified as a Senator in 74 BC (mentioned by Cicero). He is the grandson of the Mn. Aquillius who was Consul in 101 BC.

name: Fufius Calenus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer and was Consul in 47 BC. When he was Tribune of the People in 61 BC, he was instrumental in clearing P. Clodius Pulcher in the Bona Dea scandal.  He fought under Julius Caesar, but ultimately died when campaigning against Octavian at the foot of the Alps.

name: Mucius Scaevola, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Pontifex from 69 BC. His coins are inscribed CORDI, a reference to the cognomen Cordus given to the legendary hero Mucius Scaevola.

name: Vettius Sabinus, T.
bio: Republican moneyer who was likely to have been Quaestor before he issued coins in 70 BC. He later became Praetor in 59 BC (see Cicero, Flac. 85).

name: Sulpicius Galba, P.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while a curule aedile in 69 BC. He was also Pontifex by 69 BC.

name: Hosidius Geta, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, may be the man proscribed in 43 BC. He issued coins as one of the tresviri.

name: Calpurnius Piso Frugi, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, identified with Cicero's son-in-law and son of the moneyer L. Calpurnius Piso Frugi (q.v.).

name: Pomponius Musa, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Manlius Torquatus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Praetor in 49 BC.

name: Roscius Fabatus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Praetor in 49 BC. His coins reveal a Lanuvine origin.

name: Cassius Longinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was ProConsul in 48 BC.

name: Furius Brocchus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Pupius Piso, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 44 BC and son of the Consul of 61 BC, M. Pupius Piso Frugi.

name: Nonius Sufenas, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 55 BC.

name: Aemilius Scaurus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who became Praetor in 56 BC. King Aretas of Nabataea surrendered to him while Scaurus was proquaestor of Judea (recorded in Josephus, Jewish Antiquities). He may be the maternal uncle of the moneyer Mn. Acilius and a relative of Sulla. He was on trial in 54 BC under charges of extortion in his province, and was defended by Cicero. In 53 BC he was charged with ambitio and went into exile.

name: Servilius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He may be a grandson of the C. Servilius who was Praetor in 102 BC and a brother of the M. Servilius C.f. who was Tribune of the Plebs in 43 BC.

name: Considius Nonianus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Marcius Philippus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the L. Marcius Philippus who was Consul in 38 BC.

name: Cornelius Sulla, Faustus
bio: Republican moneyer who was Quaestor in 54 BC. He was the eldest child of Lucius Cornelius Sulla, the one-time dictator in Rome.

name: Memmius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who was probably Tribune of the Plebs in 54 BC.

name: Cassius Longinus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who was probably Quaestor in Hispania Ulterior in 52 BC (date uncertain). In 49 BC he was a Tribune of the People and supported Julius Caesar, who appointed him governor of Hispania Ulterior.

name: Fonteius Capito, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, usually identified with the adoptive father of P. Clodius, though without firm evidence. He may also be the Fonteius recorded as Cicero's friend.

name: Licinius Crassus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, the younger son of the Triumvir M. Licinius Crassus.

name: Plautius, A.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Tribune of the Plebs in 56, Curule Aedile in 55, and Praetor in 51 BC. He issued coins while Curule Aedile.

name: Plancius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while a Curule Aedile in 55 BC. His earlier career included time spent in Crete, which influenced the designs on his coins.

name: Pompeius Rufus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Q. Pompeius Rufus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 52 BC.

name: Valerius Messalla, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly the M. Valerius Messalla who was Consul Suffectus in 32 BC, and possibly the first-born son of the Consul of 53 BC.

name: Vinicius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Consul Suffectus in 33 BC.

name: Coelius Caldus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the C. Coelius Caldus who was quaestor in 50 BC and son of the C. Coelius Caldus who was Consul in 94 BC.

name: Sulpicius, Ser.
bio: Republican moneyer, probably  the son of the Consul of 51 BC.  The moneyer himself was probably a senator in 49 and 43 BC (cf Caesar, BC ii, 44, and Cicero Phil. Ix, 12).

name: Cornelius Lentulus Marcellinus, P.
bio: The moneyer is presumably the P. Cornelius Lentulus Marcellinus who was Quaestor in 48 BC.

name: Nerius, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, struck coins as Quaestor Urbanus in 49 BC.

name: Acilius, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, perhaps Mn. Acilius Glabrio, sister's son to the M. Aemilius Scaurus (q.v.) who was Praetor in 56 BC.

name: Coponius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cornelius Lentulus Crus, L.
mint: Apollonia Mordaieum and Asia - Moving with Pompey
bio: Republican moneyer and consul in 49 BC, who issued coins during the military campaigns of Pompey the Great (q.v.) in Apollonia and Asia in 49 BC. The coins were issued jointly with the consul C. Marcellus (q.v.) and an anonymous Quaestor, and inscribed L·LENTVLVS.

name: Claudius Marcellus, C
mint: Apollonia Mordaieum and Asia - Moving with Pompey
bio: Republican moneyer and consul in 49 BC, who issued coins during the military campaigns of Pompey the Great (q.v.) in Apollonia and Asia in 49 BC. The coins were issued jointly with the consul L. Cornelius Lentulus Crus (q.v.) and an anonymous Quaestor, and inscribed C·MARC·COS.

name: Piso, Cn
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins for Pompey the Great as Proquaestor in 49 BC.

name: Varro
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins for Pompey the Great as Proquaestor in 49 BC.

name: Hostilius Saserna, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, one of three brothers who all supported Caesar, but he is not known to have held any further office.

name: Plautius Plancus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 43 BC.

name: Licinius Nerva, A.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Antius Restio, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who may have been one of the many people proscribed in 43 BC by the Second Triumvirate.

name: Allienus, A.
bio: Republican moneyer who was ProConsul in 47 BC.

name: Licinius Crassus Iunianus Damasippus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins as Legate Propraetor in 47/6 BC, with Q. Caecilius Metellus Pius Scipio (q.v.).

name: Porcius Cato Uticensis, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, was a strong opponent of Julius Caesar and denounced the Catilinarian conspiracy (in which he tried to implicate Caesar) more fiercely than Cicero. He was informally exiled to Cyprus, but remained supportive of Pompey. After Julius Caesar's victory over Scipio at Thrapsus, Cato the Younger committed suicide.

name: Cordius Rufus, Mn.
bio: Republican moneyer, of Tusculan origin and is otherwise known only from an inscription (ILLRP 414) on which the tenure of the office of Praetor was recorded in Tusculan.

name: Carisius, T.
bio: Republican moneyer, possibly mentioned in Appian (BC v, 463).

name: Considius Paetus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Hirtius, A.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins with Julius Caesar while Praetor in 46 BC. He later became Consul in 43 BC, just after the assassination of Julius Caesar.

name: Publicius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins while Propraetor under Pompey the Younger in Spain.

name: Minatius Sabinus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, was a Legate of Cn. Pompeius the Younger.

name: Papius Celsus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: (Lollius) Palicanus
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the son of the M. Lollius Palicanus who was Praetor around 69 BC, but identifications are uncertain.

name: Valerius Acisculus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Tribune of the Plebs (date uncertain). He issued coins in 45 BC.

name: Clovius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as Praefectus with Julius Caesar while the latter was dictator.

name: Aemilius Buca, L.
bio: Republican moneyer under Julius Caesar, one of four moneyers minting in Rome during 44 BC. He is presumably a relative of Sulla, and is attested as a supporter of M. Scaurus at his trial in 54 BC.

name: Cossutius Maridianus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer under Julius Caesar, one of four moneyers minting in Rome during 44 BC, possibly a relative of the L. Cossetius Sabula (q.v.) who issued coins in 74 BC in Rome.

name: Mettius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer under Julius Caesar, one of four moneyers minting in Rome during 44 BC, he may be the same M. Mettius who appears as Legate in 58 BC.

name: Sepullius Macer, P.
bio: Republican moneyer under Julius Caesar, one of four moneyers minting in Rome during 44 BC. He may be from Patavium but is otherwise unknown.

name: Nasidius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who struck coins for Sextus Pompeius while on campaign.

name: Antonius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor in 44 BC. He was given the province of Macedonia, which was subsequently taken away from him. He tried to take the province over again early in 43 BC.

name: Flaminius Chilo, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who may be identified with the Flaminius who was a candidate for the Tribune Suffectus  in 44 BC and the Cillo who was proscribed late in 43 BC.

name: Accoleius Lariscolus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Petillius Capitolinus
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He may be the Petillius Capitolinus of Horace's Satires i.4.

name: Cestius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was one of two praetors issuing coins in 43 BC.

name: Clodius, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Livineius Regulus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Mussidius Longus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Vibius Varus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Cornelius Lentulus Spinther
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins with Brutus and Cassius. He may be the son of the Consul of 57 BC.

name: Sestius, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins for Brutus as Proquaestor.

name: Flavius Hemic, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins with Marcus Junius Brutus. His identity and cognomen is uncertain; he is probably the Flavius Noster in two of Brutus' letters to Cicero and Atticus. If he is also the Flavius of Plutarch, Brut. 51, dead at Philippi, Plutarch must be wrong in describing him as Praefectus fabrum; if he is not, he may be the C. Flavius of Appian, BC v, 207, killed at Perusia.

name: Servilius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as Legate with Brutus and Cassius.

name: (Pedanius) Costa
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as Legate under Brutus.

name: Servilius Casca Longus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins for Brutus after the assasination of Julius Caesar.

name: Plaetorius Cestianus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins under the command of Brutus.

name: Cornuficius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who was an augur and had some position of authority in a province in Africa (the details of which are unclear).

name: Staius Murcus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, involved in the civil wars between Brutus & Cassius and Octavian & Antony after the death of Julius Caesar. He issued coins while commanding independently (Africa), but was also under the command of Octavian and later under Cassius (Appian, Civil Wars, IV).

name: Clodius Vestalis, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, was later ProConsul of Crete and Cyrene.

name: Arrius Secundus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.  He may be the son of one of the two Q. Arrii who became praetors in the second half of the first century.

name: Numonius Vaala, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Servius Rufus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Barbatius Pollio, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as an officer of Mark Antony (q.v.).

name: Cocceius Nerva, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while Proquaestor under Mark Antony.

name: Gellius Poplicola, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as quaestor on behalf of Mark Antony.

name: Cornelius Balbus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins as Propraetor under Octavian during the years of the Second Triumvirate and became Consul Suffectus the following year.

name: Domitius Ahenobarbus, Cn.
bio: A partisan of Brutus and Cassius, following Julius Caesar's assassination. After fighting the Second Triumvirate at sea, he reconciled with Mark Antony, who made Ahenobarbus governor of Bithynia. He supported Antony until he grew disgusted with the latter's liaison with Cleopatra and transferred his allegiance to Octavian just before the battle of Actium. He died shortly thereafter. He issued coins as moneyer in 41 BC.

name: Salvidienus Rufus, Q.
bio: One of Octavian's (Augustus, q.v.) closest friends, despite a relatively humble origin. He was designated for Consul of 40 BC but offered to desert to Mark Antony and lost his honours when this treachery was revealed. He was killed or committed suicide in fall of 40 BC, after being condemned of treason. He issued coins with Octavian while consul designate and governor of Gaul.

name: Labienus Parthicus, Q.
bio: A general of C. Cassius Longinus, he was sent to Parthia in 43 BC to gain aid against Octavian and Mark Antony. He struck coins for the Republican forces after the assassination of Julius Caesar. He was killed in 39 BC.

name: Sempronius Gracchus, Ti.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. He was Quaestor Designatus when he issued them.

name: Voconius Vitulus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, issued coins as Quaestor designate around 40 BC.

name: Sempronius Atratinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, became Consul Suffectus in 34 BC.

name: Ventidius Bassus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer who was born in Picenum and taken as a captive to Rome during the Social Wars. He worked his way up in the Roman Army, gained the notice of Julius Caesar, and became his protégé. He eventually chose Mark Antony's side in the Antony/Octavian struggle after the assasination of Caesar, and is remembered for a superb victory against the Parthians (for which he celebrated a triumph in Rome).

name: Domitius Calvinus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer and a loyal partisan of Julius Caesar and Octavian. He held Consulships in 53 and 40 BC; he issued coins after a triumph in Spain, to which post he had been assigned by Octavian.

name: Vipsanius Agrippa, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, best known for winning the Battle of Actium. He was a lifelong friend of Octavian/Augustus, and issued coins as Consul designate in 38 BC. He held many public offices and engaged in public works when Augustus became emperor; he was named heir to Augustus and married Augustus' daughter Julia, but he died in Campania in 12 BC.

name: Junius Silanus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins with Mark Antony as quaestor.

name: Turullius, D.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins for Mark Antony.

name: Pinarius Scarpus, L.
bio: Commanded four legions under Antony in Cyrenaica, despite being an (adoptive) cousin of Octavian. After Actium he switched allegiance to Octavian, but was not allowed to serve in public office due to a perfidious nature. He issued coins for Mark Antony in 31 BC.

name: Calpurnius Piso (Frugi), Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, was later Consul Suffectus in 23 BC.

name: Quinctius Flamininus, T.
bio: Republican moneyer who was a general instrumental in the Roman conquest of Greece. He was victorious over Philip V's  forces at the Battle of Cynoscephalae in 197 BC.  He  held various offices until his death in 174 BC.

name: Oppius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer who may be identified with the only known Q. Oppius, who governed Cilicia in 88 BC.

name: Caecilius Metellus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the M. Caecilius Q.f. Q.n. Metellus who was Consul in 115 BC. His father was Q. Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus (q.v.). Coins of this type were later issued under Lucius Cornelius Sulla (q.v.).

name: Servilius Vatia, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. Coins of this type were later issued under Lucius Cornelius Sulla (q.v.).

name: Fabius Maximus, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the Q. Fabius Maximus who was Consul in 116 BC. Coins of this type were later issued under Lucius Cornelius Sulla (q.v.).

name: Domitius Ahenobarbus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer and Consul in 96 BC. He issued coins in Narbo in 118 BC as a senior monetary magistrate, jointly with the other monetary magistrates L. Licinius Crassus (q.v.), M. Aurelius Scaurus (q.v.), C. Malleolus (q.v.), L. Cosconius (q.v.), L. Pomponius (q.v.) and L. Porcius Licinus (q.v.). He is also likely to be the moneyer who issued coins in Rome in 116 or 115 BC. He may be a relative of the Cn. Domitius (q.v.) who issued coins in 128 BC, though from a different branch of the family.

name: Gargonius, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins jointly with Ogul(nius) (q.v.) and M. Ver(gilius) (q.v.). He is likely to have been the C. Gargonius who appears in Cicero's Brutus 180.

name: Ogul[nius]
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins jointly with C. Gargonius (q.v.) and M. Ver(gilius) (q.v.). He is known only from these coins, inscribed OGVL.

name: Ver[gilius], M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins jointly with C. Gargonius (q.v.) Ogul(nius) (q.v.). He may be the M. Vergilius who was Tribune of the Plebs in 87 BC. His name may alternately be M. Verginius.

name: Norbanus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer and the son of C. Norbanus (Consul 83 BC). He himself was Praetor in 43 and Consul in 38 BC.

name: Cornelius Sulla Felix, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, the dictator of the Roman republic 81-80 BC. He was a patrician who marched on Rome twice but ultimately gave up his dictatorial powers.

name: Crepusius, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins.

name: Mamilius Limetanus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably a son of the C. Mamilius Limetanus who was Tribune of the Plebs in 109 BC.

name: Marcius Censorinus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer, presumably the father of the L.Marcius Censorinus who was Consul in 39 BC. If he was not proscribed, he may be identified with the Censorinus who was attested as Legate in 70 BC.

name: Cornelius Lentulus Marcellinus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer who Issued coins as Quaestor in 76-75 BC. He was later Praetor in 60 BC and governor of Syria in 59-58 BC, where he may also have issued coins. He was consul in 56 BC.

name: Pompeius Magnus, Cn.
alt_name: Pompey the Great~Pompeius Cn.f.Sex.N. Magnus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, who issued coins in 71 BC and as proConsul in 49 BC. He was a member of the First Triumvirate (though a rival of Crassus'), and after the dissolution of that alliance became an enemy of Julius Caesar. He died in 48 BC, the victim of an assasination in Egypt.

name: Plaetorius Cestianus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Praetor around 64 BC.

name: Aemilius Lepidus Paullus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Consul in 50 BC. He falsely claimed to be descended from Lucius Aemilius Paullus. He issued coins solely and jointly with L Scribonius Libo (q.v.) in 62 BC.

name: Scribonius Libo, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who may possibly be the same Scribonius Libo who was Consul in 34 BC, but may alternately be said Consul's father. He issued coins both solely and jointly with L Aemilius Lepidus Paullus (q.v.).

name: Aemilius Lepidus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, M. Aemilius Lepidus, III vir r.p.c (member of the Second Triumvirate with Octavian and Antony).

name: Plautius Hypsaeus, P.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Praetor around 55 BC. He issued coins solely in 60 BC and jointly with M. Aemilius Scaurus (q.v.) while Curule Aedile in 58 BC.

name: Junius Brutus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, best known as one of the conspirator against Julius Caesar. He fought with Pompey against Julius Caesar at Pharsalus, but was pardoned by the victorius Caesar and became his supporter. He grew concerned with Caesar's unchecked growing power and was persuaded by Cassius to join the plot against the dictator. After the assasination, he was persuaded to honor Caesar's will and went into exile on Crete. He died fighting Octavian's forces at the second battle at Philippi.

name: Sicinius, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, known only from his coins. These were issued solely and jointly with C. Coponius (q.v.).

name: Iulius Caesar, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, C. Julius Caesar, or Julius Caesar. He is best known for his role in the transformation of the Roman Republic into the Roman Empire. He conquered Gaul and was a member of the First Triumvirate, but after the collapse of that political alliance became an enemy of Pompey the Great's and crossed the Rubicon to march on Rome as part of the struggle. He attained multiple Consulships and was named dictator perpetuus, a move which sparked the jealousy of C. Cassius and concern of M. Junius Brutus. These two men headed the plot which led to the assasination of Julius Caesar on March 15, 44 BC.

name: Vibius Pansa Caetronianus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Consul in 43 BC and was probably the adoptive son of the C. Vibius Pansa (q.v.) who issued coins in 90 BC.

name: Iunius Brutus Albinus, D.
bio: Republican moneyer who was Consul Designatus in 42 BC

name: Caecilius Metellus Pius Scipio, Q.
bio: Republican moneyer, was Consul in 52 BC. He became father-in-law of Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus. He commanded the army at Thapsus, and was killed in battle against Gaius Julius Caesar's legions.

name: Eppius
bio: Republican moneyer, a Legatus fisci castrensis (financial official in the province). He issued coins jointly with Q. Caecilius Metellus Pius Scipio (q.v.) and later with Sextus Pompeius Magnus Pius (q.v.).

name: Pompeius Magnus, Cn.
bio: Republican moneyer, was the oldest son of Pompey the Great. He supported his father in the campaigns against Julius Caesar, and supported the Pompeian cause until his death.

name: Munatius Plancus, L.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins while Praefectus Urbis in 45 BC, and later under the command of Mark Antony. He managed to survive the complex political currents in the first century BC by constantly shifting his allegiance. He was consul in 42 BC and served as ProConsul in various provinces. Contemporary sources suggest he was not well-respected.

name: Pompeius Magnus Pius, Sextus
bio: Youngest son of Pompey the Great (q.v.), he was not involved much in politics until the death of his father in Egypt (48 BC) when he fought against the forces of Antony and Octavian. He escaped after the Battle of Munda in 45 BC and built up a power base in Sicily. He signed the Pact of Misenum in 39 BC, but was attacked in the Battle of Messina (37 BC), escaping after Agrippa destroyed his navy (36 BC). He was caught in Miletus in 35 BC, where he was captured and executed without trial, on the orders of Mark Antony. He issued coins in Spain and Sicily from 45 BC.

name: Antonius, M.
bio: Republican moneyer, born around 83 BC and is best remembered for his affair with Cleopatra VII of Egypt. He was a distant cousin of Julius Caesar, and supported him and his adoptive son Octavian. With Octavian he sought to avenge the assasination of Caesar, fighting the forces of Brutus and Cassius, but the two allies became enemies. Antony committed suicide during the final days of the battle of Actium, as Octavian overpowered his and Cleopatra's combined forces.

name: Caesar, C.
bio: Roman emperor. Born C. Octavius, adopted by Julius Caesar (q.v.) as C. Julius Caesar in 44 BC, then Imperator Caesar Divi Filius (known as Octavian). Took new name of Augustus in 27 BC. Became first Roman emperor. Died 19 August AD 14. Deified 17 September AD 14. He issued coins as moneyer in 43 BC.

name: Aquinus, M.
bio: Republican moneyer who issued coins with Cassius as legate.

name: Cassius Longinus, C.
bio: Republican moneyer, best known as one of the conspirators agains Julius Caesar. Cassius was Quaestor in 53 BC under M. Licinius Crassus, and later governed Syria for two years as Proquaestor. He was Tribune of the Plebs in 49 BC, fled Rome when Caesar crossed the Rubicon, and thereafter nursed growing resentment towards Caesar. He committed suicide in 42 BC.
